</keywordset>

</bookinfo>

<chapter id="introduction">
<title>Introduction</title>


<para>
KGpg is a system tray applet. It means that when you start it, it docks in your kicker.

<screenshot>
<screeninfo>KGpg system tray applet</screeninfo>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject>
<imagedata fileref="kicker.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>

You can then access KGpg by clicking on the icon. A left mouse click will bring up all possible actions, while a right mouse click
will bring up the configuration and help options. Here are the main features:
</para>


<para>
1- <emphasis>Encrypt/Decrypt Clipboard</emphasis>: Allows you to encrypt/decrypt the content of the clipboard. 
Encryption will paste the encrypted text in the clipboard, while decryption will open KGpg's editor to show you the 
decrypted text.
</para>

<para>
2- <emphasis>Encrypt/Decrypt Files</emphasis>: Allows you to encrypt/decrypt files. 
You can encrypt a file by right clicking on it in &konqueror; or on your Desktop,
and selecting "Encrypt File". You can also open KGpg's Editor and, in menu <guimenu>File</guimenu>->
<guimenuitem>Encrypt File</guimenuitem>. To decrypt a file, 
just left click on it to decrypt it, or use KGpg's editor, menu <guimenu>File</guimenu>->
<guimenuitem>Decrypt File</guimenuitem>.
You can also drop a file/text on the applet icon to encrypt/decrypt it.
</para>

<para>
3- <emphasis>KGpg editor</emphasis>: This is a simple editor with buttons to perform encryption/decryption/signing.
You can drop an encrypted file in the editor window to decrypt it.
</para>

<para>
4- <emphasis>KGpg key manager</emphasis>: Allows you to perform all basic key operations: create, import, export, 
delete, sign,...
</para>

</chapter>

<chapter id="using-kgpg">
<title>Using Kgpg</title>

<para>
Kgpg is basically a gnupg frontend. It supports many gpg features.
For more infos on how encryption works, you 
can find some tutorials on <ulink url="http://gnupg.org">http://gnupg.org</ulink>.
</para>

<sect1 id="key-generation">
<title>Generating a key</title>
<para>
The first thing you have to do to use Kgpg is to generate a key. If you don't have one already, 
Kgpg will automatically pop up the key generation dialog at the first startup. You can also access 
it in the Key Manager->Keys menu->Generate Key Pair.
</para>

<screenshot>
<screeninfo>Key generation dialog</screeninfo>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject>
<imagedata fileref="keygen.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>

<para>
Simply enter your name, E-Mail adress and click ok. This will generate a standard gpg key. If you want more 
options, you can click on the Expert mode button, which will bring up a konsole window with all of gpg's options.
</para>

</sect1>
<sect1 id="encryption">
<title>Encrypting your data</title>

<sect2 id="konqui">
<title>Encrypting a file from Konqueror</title>
<para>
Right click on the file you want to encrypt. Choose Encrypt file in the popup menu. You will then be prompted with the Public key 
selection dialog. Choose your key and click Encrypt. The encrypted file will be saved with a .asc or .gpg extension 
depending on whether you choosed ASCII encryption or not. You can also encrypt a file from Kgpg: in the File menu->Encrypt file.
</para>

<screenshot>
<screeninfo>Here's a screenshot of konqueror's menu</screeninfo>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject>
<imagedata fileref="menu.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>

</sect2>


<sect2 id="drop">
<title>Encrypting a file/text with KGpg's applet</title>
<para>
Simply drop your file on KGpg's system tray applet. If it is an uncrypted file, KGpg will pop up the 
key selection dialog (see below). Select the encryption key, and the encrypted file will be saved.
If you drop text, the encrypted text will be pasted to the clipboard.
You can also encrypt clipboard by selecting the "encrypt clipboard" item in applet's menu.
</para>

<screenshot>
<screeninfo>Here's a screenshot of the key selection window</screeninfo>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject>
<imagedata fileref="keys.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>
<para>
For more infos on the encryption options "ASCII armor", "Allow encryption with untrusted keys" and "Symmetrical encryption", please
refer to gpg's documentation or man pages.
</para>

</sect2>


<sect2 id="editor">
<title>Encrypting a text from Kgpg's editor</title>
<para>
This is as simple as clicking on the Encrypt button. You will then be prompted with the Public key 
selection dialog. Choose your key and click Encrypt again. The encrypted message will appear in
the editor window.
</para>
</sect2>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="decryption">
<title>Decrypting your data</title>


<sect2 id="konq-dec">
<title>Decrypting a file from Konqueror</title>
<para>
Left click on the file you want to decrypt. Enter your passphrase and it's done. You can also drag an encrypted text file 
and drop it into Kgpg's editor window. It will then ask the passphrase and open the decrypted text in Kgpg's editor. 
You can even drop remote files ! You can also go in Kgpg's menu File->Decrypt file and choose a file to decrypt.
</para>
</sect2>

<sect2 id="kicker-dec">
<title>Decrypting a text/file with KGpg's applet</title>
<para>
You can drop an encrypted file/text on KGpg's system tray applet. You will then be prompted for password, and 
the decrypted file/text willl be saved or opened in KGpg's editor depending from how you configured the applet.
You can also decrypt clipboard with the "decrypt clipboard" menu entry of KGpg's applet
</para>
</sect2>

<sect2 id="editor-dec">
<title>Decrypting a text from the editor</title>
<para>
Copy or Drag and Drop the text you want to decrypt, and click on the Decrypt button. You will be promped for the 
passphrase and that's it.
</para>
</sect2>


</sect1>

<sect1 id="manage">
<title>Key Management</title>

<para>
All basic key management options can be performed through Kgpg. To do this, open the key management 
window from the KGpg's applet menu. Currently supported actions: Key generation and deletion, 
signing a key, import and export, choosing a default key, key infos.
To import/export public keys, you can use drag and drop or the Copy/Paste keyboard shortcuts.
</para>

<screenshot>
<screeninfo>Here's a screenshot of key management</screeninfo>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject>
<imagedata fileref="keymanage.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="options">
<title>Configuring KGpg</title>

<para>
KGpg's configuration is accessible through KGpg's applet menu (right click on the applet).
You can set default parameters for encryption, decryption, user interface and applet. 
Most encryption options are directly related to gpg and are documented in it's man page.
</para>

<screenshot>
<screeninfo>Here's a screenshot of the option dialog</screeninfo>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject>
<imagedata fileref="options.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>

</sect1>

</chapter>


